observations.recommendation:
Inventory Committee to conduct and prepare report on the Physical Count of Road Network of the municipality;



GSO-Designate to prepare and submit RLRN, maintain LRI, Road Map, and keep LRNPC for all roads and its components;



Office-in-Charge (OIC) – Municipal Engineer to provide the GSO-Designate and MA a report on the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, with consideration to road intersections; and



Municipal Accountant to update the general ledger of the road network of the Municipality, prepare lapsing schedule for the depreciation and comply with the disclosure requirements for road network system in compliance to COA Circular No. 2015-005 dated November 23, 2015, in order to present fairly the FS of the Municipality.

Whenever applicable, implement the PPAs listed above as embodied in the MDP;



Revisit the plans and budget embodied in the Municipal EDP and identify the necessities of the listed projects therein, otherwise identify more appropriate and responsive PPAs; and



Appropriate the unexpended balances derived from previous implementation of projects to new projects that are aligned to the purpose of the 20% DF. These would ensure that benefits intended for the Municipality’s populace will be met.

effectively and judiciously plan the PPAs to be included in a comprehensive MDRRM Plan and Annual Investment Program (AIP) by considering its feasibility and necessity aligned to the national, regional and provincial framework and policies and which could be strictly implemented for a given timeframe;







fully implement PPAs under the LDRRMF to mitigate the socio-economic and environmental impacts of the unforeseeable disasters in the Municipality and disaster risks especially projected climate risks and to enhance disaster preparedness and response capabilities and avoid potential damages to the community;



properly coordinate with concerned officials to address difficulties that hindered/ prevented the full implementation of the PPAs identified and stated in the MDRRM Plan for CY 2022 effectively and efficiently; and



maximize the utilization of LDRRMF for both current and continuing appropriations to achieve the objective of strengthening the capacity of the Municipality to build a disaster resilient community and enhance the disaster preparedness and response capabilities.

Strictly observe the provisions of Sections 305 and 337 of RA No. 7160;







Exercise prudence in the utilization of funds to eliminate cash overdraft; and







Require the Local Finance Committee and MA to determine the underlying causes of the cash deficit in order to properly address the condition.

Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical inventory in order to present a realistic balance of property accounts and make a fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements;



MA to:

maintain updated PPE Ledger Cards;



submit a complete and accurate Lapsing Schedule with specific details of the PPE to the Audit Team to verify its correctness and include the date of acquisition and estimated useful life of the PPE to properly present the carrying amount;

coordinate with the Municipal Assessor to analyze and investigate the noted discrepancies on the Land account and make the necessary adjustments as appropriate;

coordinate with the GSO-Designate to gather the documents necessary in updating or reconstructing their records to be able to provide depreciation to the subject PPE items noted in the audit observations, and for the MA to effect the necessary adjustments of the depreciation expense for the year, accumulated depreciation for prior years and the corresponding amount to the government equity account;

prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the misclassification of PPE items mentioned in the noted observations. Thereafter, ensure that all PPEs are properly recorded based on the nature of the procured items; and



Property/Supply Officer to always maintain for each class of PPE a Property Card for the recording of PPE with information as to its description, custody, and disposal.

Instruct the BAC to prepare a resolution declaring and justifying that direct retail purchase as the chosen mode of procurement for POL products and delegation of the procurement to specific officials, personnel or committee or office the conduct of such purchases. Likewise, the Municipal Mayor shall prepare and issue an issuance or an order for the same purpose;



Ensure that each office under the Municipality provide a necessary estimate of needed POL products within the fiscal year, including provisions for foreseeable emergencies based on historical records, which will be subjected to direct retail purchase and consolidated in the preparation of the Annual Procurement Plan; and



Make sure that direct purchases are made from any available retailers, dealers or gas stations at retail pump price and the requirement must be intended to be used for any official government vehicles and equipment for immediate consumption.

We recommended Management to require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct and prepare report on the Physical Count of Road Network of the municipality;
GSO-Designate to prepare and submit RLRN, maintain LRI, Road Map, and keep LRNPC for all roads and its components;
Office-in-Charge (OIC) – Municipal Engineer to provide the GSO-Designate and MA a report on the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, with consideration to road intersections; and
MA to update the general ledger of the road network of the Municipality, prepare lapsing schedule for the depreciation and comply with the disclosure requirements for road network system in compliance to COA Circular No. 2015-005 dated November 23, 2015, in order to present fairly the FS of the Municipality.

The Management assured the Audit Team that the concerned offices will coordinate with each other to implement the recommendations enumerated above.

We recommended that Management require the:
a. Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical inventory in order to present a realistic balance of property accounts and make a fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements;
b. Municipal Accountant to:
 maintain updated PPE Ledger Cards;
 submit a complete and accurate Lapsing Accounting Schedule with specific details of the PPE items for the Audit Team to verify its correctness and include the date of acquisition and estimated useful life of its PPE to properly present its carrying amount;
 coordinate with the Municipal Assessor to analyze and investigate the noted discrepancies on the Land account and make the necessary adjustments as appropriate;
 coordinate with the GSO to gather the documents necessary in updating or reconstructing their records to be able to provide depreciation to the subject PPE items in the various PPE item G. of the noted observations, and for the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjustments of the depreciation expense for the year, accumulated depreciation for prior years and the corresponding amount to the government equity account;
 reclassify to the proper Inventory account tangible assets with estimated useful life of more than one year but small enough to be considered and recorded as PPE. Moreover, record the items as expense upon issuance of the small tangible items; and
 prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the misclassification of PPE items mentioned in item h. of the noted observations. Thereafter, ensure that all PPEs are properly recorded based on the nature of the procured items.
c. Property/Supply Officer to always maintain for each class of PPE a Property Card for the recording of PPE with information as to its description, custody and disposal; and
d. Acting GSO to:
 tender the corresponding Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) to the personnel to whom the items are issued for proper monitoring, control and accountability;
 act on disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance to the guidelines prescribed under COA Circular No. 89-286.

We recommended that Management instruct the:
a. Municipal Accountant to:
 immediately correct the accounting errors and henceforth compute the depreciation in accordance with the provisions of numbers 12 and 14 of Item IV of COA Circular No. 2015-008, paragraph 59 of IPSAS 17 and item e.1 of DPWH DO No. 176 s. 2015;
 recognize the cost of labor of various projects and make necessary adjusting entries to reduce the government equity account and increase the road network account in accordance to paragraph 30 of IPSAS 17;
 immediately coordinate with the Municipal Engineer and Acting GSO for the completion of the inventory of roads and bridges that were implemented and completed prior to CY 2016 in order to reinstate these in the books; and
 coordinate with the GSO for the reconciliation of their records on or before the end of each year.
b. Municipal Engineer to periodically provide the Municipal Accountant and the Acting GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of the road components for road projects as basis of the latter to update their respective records/inventory;
c. Municipal Assessor to immediately coordinate with the Municipal Engineer for the valuation of the related road lots and provide the list of values to the Municipal Accountant and Acting GSO for proper recording thereof until the end of the third quarter of CY 2021 in compliance with number 2 of Item IV of COA Circular No. 2015-008; and
d. Municipal GSO to maintain and periodically update the Municipality Government’s Local Road Inventory and Road Map and include the value of the road lot components provided by the Municipality Assessor.

We recommended that Management:
a. Cause the Inventory Management Committee to conduct the regular physical count of inventories and furnish a copy of the RCPI to the Office of the Auditor;
b. Require the Acting GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to conduct periodic reconciliation of property and accounting records and the immediate verification of discrepancies, if any, to effect the necessary adjustment/s in the Municipality books; and
c. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
 record all purchases of inventory items as inventory except those paid out of the petty cash fund;
 record Inventory expenses based on the RSMI submitted by the MTO/Acting GSO;
 coordinate with official/department heads concerned for the proper accounting of donation/s received by the Municipality whether in cash or in kind; and
 immediately prepare an adjusting journal entry to reflect the correct balances of the Inventory accounts.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
a. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the RPT and SEFT Receivable and make duly supported adjustments, if any, to present fairly the financial statements;
b. Formulate polices to improve the timely collection of taxes.

Again, we recommended the following:
b.1) The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to properly evaluate the completeness of Bidding Documents, Eligibility and Technical requirements and other documents before recommending the award of contracts to the Municipal Mayor;
b.2) The Municipal Accountant must require all pertinent documents before certifying the disbursement vouchers as to the completeness of supporting documents in line with Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 to avoid doubts on the legality, validity and propriety of transactions.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
a. The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the municipality and render a Report on the Physical count of the Road Networks System.
b. The Municipal General Service Officer to:
 b.1. Render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map; 
 b.2. Regularly maintain and update the Registry of Public Infrastructures for Roads; 
 b.3. Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.
c. The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Service Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.
d. The Municipal Accountant to:
 d.1. Prepare and maintain a Local Road Network Ledger Card;
 d.2. Keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network;
 d.3. Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year.
 d.4. Disclose in the NFS the length covered by the system, additions and reductions, major repairs and regular maintenance for the year.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
a. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the RPT and SEFT Receivable and make duly supported adjustments, if any, to present fairly the financial statements;
b. Take into consideration the procedures on the collection of taxes laid down under RA No. 7160;
c. Enforce collection of the unpaid delinquent taxes;
d. Formulate polices to improve the timely collection of taxes.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
a. See to it that drugs and medicines being procured by the municipality are obtained from authorized suppliers, distributors and/or manufacturers as stated in their License to Operate and List of Sources;
b. Ensure the authenticity, safety and effectiveness and quality of procured drugs and medicines by requiring the supplier to submit together with their bids and/or quotations Certificate of Product Registration, Certificate of Good Manufacturing Practice and Batch Release Certificates from Bureau of Foods and Drugs Administration;
c. Adherence to the provisions of Administrative Order No. 43 series 1999, Administrative Order No. 47-A series of 2001 dated August 30, 2001 and Administrative Order No. 103 series 2002 issued by the Department of Health, RA No. 3720 otherwise known as the Foods, Drugs and Devices and Cosmetics Act as amended by Executive Order No. 175, COA Circular No. 2012-001 and PD No. 1445.

Again, we recommended that management:
a) Present supporting documents of recorded year-end payables to establish their validity, propriety and existence; 
b) Revisit the existing process of procurement of the municipal government starting from planning, budgeting and accounting and design an effective monitoring system with the objective of reflecting the true amount of Accounts Payable duly supported by proper and necessary documents.

We recommended that management take the following courses of action:
a. Instruct the Municipal Treasury and Accountant and Municipal Records to reconcile the RPT and SEF Tax Receivable and make duly supported adjustments, if any, to present fairly the financial statements;
b. Take into consideration the procedures on the collection of taxes laid down under RA 7160;
c. Enforce collection of the unpaid delinquent taxes;
d. Formulate polices to improve the timely collection of taxes.

We recommended that management take the following courses of action:
a. See to it that drugs and medicines being procured by the municipality are obtained from authorized suppliers, distributors and/or manufacturers as stated in their License to Operate and List of Sources;
b. Ensure the authenticity, safety and effectiveness and quality of procured drugs and medicines by requiring the supplier to submit together with their bids and/or quotations Certificate of Product Registration, Certificate of Good Manufacturing Practice and Batch Release Certificates from Bureau of Foods and Drugs Administration;
c. Adherence to the provisions of the Administrative Order No. 43 series 1999, Administrative Order No. 47-A series of 2001 dated August 30, 2001 and Administrative Order No. 103 series 2002 issued by the Department of Health, Republic Act No. 3720 otherwise known as the Foods, Drugs and Devices and Cosmetics Act as amended by Executive Order No. 175, COA Circular 2012-001 and Presidential Decree No. 1445.

We recommended and management agreed to:
a) Comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of RA 9184 on the warranty security for the purchase of goods in the form of retention money or special bank guarantee equivalent to not less than one percent (1%) of the purchase price, to ensure that the supplier will correct any manufacturing defects that may be found within the warranty period;
b) Ensure that all vouchers on the procurement of supplies, materials, equipment, and motor vehicles, are adequately documented as set forth in the provisions of Item 9.1.3.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001;
c) Ensure timely posting of Notices of Award in PhilGEPS;
d) Submit explanation/justification as to why deliveries of procured meals and snacks did not coincide with the procurement timeline; and adhere strictly to RA 9184 and its 2016 IRR;
e) Meticulously review contracts and refrain from awarding contracts to non-responsive bidders as provided in RA 9184 and its 2016 Revised IRR;
f) Provide basis in awarding the contract and ensure completeness of documents; and
 g) Post invitations/awards/contracts in PhilGEPS as required and include printouts as supporting documents.

We recommended management the following:
a. Require the contractor to fast track the completion of the project to attain its desired purpose and impose applicable sanctions and penalties, if warranted;
b. The Monitoring and Evaluation Committee faithfully monitor and evaluate the implementation of the project so that any cause of suspension and/ or problems in the course of the implementation can be immediately addressed.

We recommended that management take the following courses of action:

a. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to
reconcile the RPT and SEF Tax Receivable and make duly supported
adjustments, if any, to present fairly the financial statements;

b. Take into consideration the procedures on the collection of taxes laid
down under RA 7160;

c. Enforce collection of the unpaid delinquent taxes;

d. Formulate polices to improve the timely collection of taxes.
